<br>
But when the d00ds, the beggars, the trainers, the people who spout obscenities, the people who go out of their way to deride role-playing, the total power gamers and the board trolls do it that's ok?<br>
<br>
One group gets called &quot;police&quot; or more often &quot;Nazis&quot; for trying to keep the server to the spirit it was set up in (a server for people who prefer to role-play NOT a server where role-playing is preferred) the others get defended.  It seems small minded and unfair to me. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/uzeldagisravensoul.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Zeldagis Ravensoul</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 40<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(8/1/02 1:27:39 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1135.topic&index=37>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   It does work both ways</span><hr size=1> I'll agree that it should work both ways, and that in many cases, it does.  There is no rule to enforce roleplaying in the game, nor should there be.  However, there is an ignore command for a reason, and I would suggest you use it.  It isn't up to you or me to decide how others should play the game.  You might think the server would be better if everyone acted the way you want them to, but in truth would it be?  <br>
<br>
In short, people that get upset because someone say &quot;sow plz&quot; are no less pathetic than the person who asks that on a RP preferred server.<br>
